Left_Text: [COL] title [VAL] punch! 5 in 1 home design [COL] description [VAL] home renovation software takes a big leap forward with 5 in 1 home design from punch! a package that lets you draw an imagined future home or work on altering the one you have--without investing in building materials or architects up front! divided into a series of specialized applications this program makes it simple to hone room layouts design decks fine-tune furnishing designs and landscape any size or shape of building lot. and when the individual pieces are polished 5 in 1 home design pulls everything together into the big picture of your dreams. unlike many comparable packages this package provides a fast and streamlined process for drawing floor plans from scratch. moving wall by wall rather than room by room a user can lay out everything in detail. whether you are reconstructing an existing house or dreaming big the program's learning process is swift. it is still possible to end up struggling to convince the package that an interior room is indeed inside the house (and thus deserving of carpet rather than lawn) but these glitches are rare and relatively easy to amend. anyone interested in having a basic plan done both painlessly and fast will love the interface this program offers. other tools in 5 in 1 home design allow you to walk through the three-dimensional model of your house print out pieces of a model so you can build it yourself and fit the home inside and out with furnishings and finishes. you can switch to these tools without ever shutting off the core floor plan moving to an overhead view of the house and back then breezing into a furniture-building application. to minimize headaches all the data on each house is kept in a single file. in short punch! 5 in 1 home design will help you put together homes just as you imagine them. the power so handily available in this design program makes it an obvious first choice for those new to home design software and a real boon for anyone looking to brainstorm ideas for constructing decorating or renovating a house. --alyx dellamonica [COL] manufacturer [VAL] punch! Left_Text: [COL] title [VAL] Blood Ties (3) [COL] abstract [VAL] The Wilsons go on television to offer a reward. The newspapers are making the Homicide unit look bad and Barnfather wants quick resolution to the case. The man (and his wife) who gave up Junior Bunk are murdered; Falsone and Lewis investigate. The only survivor, their young son, is brought in to find out what he remembers. His memories-- and a recorded phone message-- lead Stivers to believe a former member of the Narcotics unit is involved. The officer cops to a deal that implicates Georgia Rae Mahoney, though Giardella doesn't want to pursue that yet. Falsone's questioning of the Mahoney shooting leads Cox to doubt her actions at the time of the investigation. Incriminating evidence leads the detectives to Hal Wilson being their prime suspect. Frank goes to interview Felix and Hal Wilson; son and father confront some long-standing issues. Hal's confession is inadmissible in court, the Wilsons leave the Baltimore area, and the case remains officially open. After they are able to implicate the cop in the shooting, as a bonus they discover the body of her string-pulling father. Ballard suffers from an allergic reaction to crabs. Falsone finds out that the case against Georgia Rae Mahoney is going to be dropped because of a lack of evidence. He suspects that the whole Mahoney thing is going to blow up in the department's face, because he knows the Mahoney shooting didn't go down the way Stivers, Kellerman and Lewis reported it. Right_Text: [COL] title [VAL] The Long Paddock [COL] abstract [VAL] 'Enthusiastic young vet Jill Blake (Victoria Thaine) arrives in the dusty one-horse town of Paringa to find only a curt note directing her to her spartan new home. When her new boss, the notoriously ''difficult'' Kate McDonald (Rachel Ward), turns up, her attitude is as dry as the drought-stricken landscape...Set to work immediately, Jill encounters many of the problems of dry-land farming in stark relief: a farmer who can cope with neither the drought nor his mounting debts; another forced off his land by the bank; and a third confronting the vexed issues of succession and future planning. Then there's the spectre of a notifiable sheep disease, the mere mention of which turns Kate's prickly attitude to open hostility.It's clear that Kate has a stronger connection to the land and the people on it than just treating their animals. Kate tells Jill that she either accepts her way of working or she needn't bother unpacking her bags. If that weren't enough to scare Jill off, there's the mysterious locked room in Kate's house, and the light from its window in the middle of the night... Then, by chance, detectives discovered that on the night she died Kim had been in the company of a local miner, 24-year-old Graham Potter, who had suddenly disappeared. A national manhunt led to his eventual surrender. Potter was convicted of Kim Barry’s murder and sentenced to life imprisonment. No motive was ever established for the killing and Potter, who was released in 1996 after serving 15 years, still declares he is innocent. Right_Text: [COL] title [VAL] Episode 13 [COL] abstract [VAL] Time has passed by; F4 are now college students and Jandi is in her senior year at high school (12th grade). Jandi keeps practicing swimming and works part-time, and awaits Junpyo. Jandi finds out that she won’t be able to swim anymore and now it’s too late to cure. Confused and toubled, Jandi goes to Macau to meet Junpyo. She gets surprised at the magnificent look of Hotel Shinhwa, but doesn’t get overwhelmed. However, when Jandi finally gets a chance to see Junpyo, he only gives her the cold shoulder.
